summary: Host-mutation tests, shared by every plan

# The tier tag names what a test needs underneath — plans filter on it:
#   3 — anywhere a --root prefix is enough (containers included)
#   4 — a real kernel, a real libvirtd, and a real reboot
#   5 — hardware CI cannot rent: an emulated IOMMU, or your own desk

/lifecycle:
    summary: apply, re-apply, undo — byte-identical
    description: |
        The central promise: undo restores the tree the apply found. Runs over
        every fixture preflight lets through, so the guarantee is asserted
        across the topology matrix rather than on one reference host.
    test: ./lifecycle.sh
    duration: 15m
    tier: 3

/refusal:
    summary: apply refuses a failed host, writes nothing
    description: |
        A refused apply must be inert. Covers the fixtures that fail preflight
        for distinct reasons — dirty IOMMU group, no iGPU, duplicate GPU IDs,
        pre-existing vfio config, no reset support.
    test: ./refusal.sh
    duration: 10m
    tier: 3

/fault:
    summary: a killed apply still undoes cleanly
    description: |
        SIGKILLs the binary after each line it emits and requires undo to put
        the tree back. This is what proves the journal is write-ahead.
    test: ./fault.sh
    duration: 15m
    tier: 3

/reboot:
    summary: the up pipeline across two real reboots
    description: |
        The only tier where the BLS edit reaches the running kernel, dracut
        regenerates a real initramfs, and the domain lands in a live libvirtd.
        Uses tmt-reboot, so the state machine is asserted at its actual reboot
        boundary rather than simulated with a written /proc/cmdline.
    test: ./reboot.sh
    duration: 45m
    tier: 4

/hugepages:
    summary: the hook's hugepage pool, against a real kernel
    description: |
        Under a --root prefix nr_hugepages is an ordinary file that reads back
        what was written, so the retry-on-readback loop and the shortfall
        rollback are unreachable. Here the kernel allocates physical pages and
        reports what it actually managed — the difference between a user
        getting an explanation and getting an opaque QEMU out-of-memory.
    test: ./hugepages.sh
    duration: 10m
    tier: 4

/media:
    summary: real loop ioctls against a real ISO
    description: |
        LOOP_CTL_GET_FREE, LOOP_CONFIGURE, and the udf-then-iso9660 mount
        fallback need CAP_SYS_ADMIN in the initial user namespace, so unit
        tests swap the whole mount seam for a directory. This is the only
        place the ISO writer's output meets a real kernel filesystem driver.
    test: ./media.sh
    duration: 10m
    tier: 4

/vfio:
    summary: the IOMMU and the vfio-pci bind, for real
    description: |
        The only tier where the kernel rather than a fixture answers. Its guest
        has an emulated IOMMU, so intel_iommu=on written by apply actually
        populates /sys/kernel/iommu_groups, and the qemu hook really evicts a
        device to vfio-pci and hands it to libvirtd. Identity is the one thing
        still synthetic — three per-file bind mounts over vendor, device and
        class, leaving every attribute the hook operates on real.
    test: ./vfio.sh
    duration: 60m
    tier: 5

/desk:
    summary: the fixtures, checked against real hardware
    description: |
        Read-only detect, preflight, and status against the machine this runs
        on. Every golden in the suite derives from hwtest.Roots, which is
        hand-written; this is the only thing that ever asks whether those
        fixtures resemble a real host. Never runs in CI — there is no rentable
        machine with the target topology.
    test: ./desk.sh
    duration: 5m
    tier: 5
